  <h1 id="hd_id941629155075179"><variable id="wildcards_h1"><link href="text/swriter/guide/search_regexp.xhp" name="wildcards_link">Using Wildcards in Calc Formulas</link></variable></h1>
  <paragraph role="paragraph" id="par_id571629155308959">Wildcards are special characters that can be used in search strings that are passed as arguments to some Calc formulas. The use of wildcards enables the definition of more advanced search criteria in a single search string.</paragraph>
  <paragraph role="paragraph" id="par_id391629156224638">%PRODUCTNAME Calc supports either <emph>wildcards</emph> or <emph>regular expressions</emph> as arguments depending on the current application settings. By default %PRODUCTNAME Calc is set to support wildcards instead of regular expressions.</paragraph>
  <tip id="par_id551629156504794">To make sure wildcards are supported, go to <menuitem>Tools - Options - %PRODUCTNAME Calc - Calculate</menuitem> and check if the option <emph>Enable wildcards in formulas</emph> is selected. Note that you can use this dialog to switch to regular expressions by choosing <emph>Enable regular expressions in formulas</emph> or choose to not support both wildcards and regular expressions.</tip>
  <paragraph role="paragraph" id="par_id141629156913731">The following wildcards are supported:</paragraph>
  <list type="unordered">
    <listitem>
        <paragraph id="par_id241629157077619" role="listitem"><emph>? (question mark)</emph> matches any single character. For example, the search string "b?g" matches “bag” and “beg” but will not match "boog" or "mug".</paragraph>
    </listitem>
    <listitem>
        <paragraph id="par_id551629157078098" role="listitem"><emph>* (asterisk)</emph> matches any sequence of characters, including an empty string. For example, the search string "*cast" will match “cast”, “forecast”, and “outcast”, but will not match "forecaster".</paragraph>
    </listitem>
    <listitem>
        <paragraph id="par_id761629157078290" role="listitem"><emph>~ (tilde)</emph> escapes the special meaning of a question mark, asterisk, or tilde character that follows immediately after the tilde character. For example, the search string "why~?" matches “why?”.</paragraph>
    </listitem>
  </list>
  <tip id="par_id1001629157561261">Wildcards are supported in %PRODUCTNAME Calc and in Microsoft Excel. Therefore, if interoperability between both applications is needed, choose to work with wildcards instead of regular expressions.</tip>
  <h2 id="hd_id671629158766165">Supported Formulas</h2>
  <paragraph role="paragraph" id="par_id161629158785887">Wildcards are supported by the following formulas:</paragraph>
  <list type="unordered">
    <listitem>
        <paragraph id="par_id441629158810517" role="listitem"><emph>Database formulas:</emph> DAVERAGE, DCOUNT, DCOUNTA, DGET, DMAX, DMIN, DPRODUCT, DSTDEV, DSTDEVP, DSUM, DVAR, DVARP.</paragraph>
    </listitem>
    <listitem>
        <paragraph id="par_id321629158810916" role="listitem"><emph>Conditional formulas:</emph> AVERAGEIF, AVERAGEIFS, COUNTIF, COUNTIFS, MAXIFS, MINIFS, SUMIF and SUMIFS.</paragraph>
    </listitem>
    <listitem>
        <paragraph id="par_id941629158811325" role="listitem"><emph>Lookup formulas:</emph> HLOOKUP, LOOKUP and VLOOKUP.</paragraph>
    </listitem>
    <listitem>
        <paragraph id="par_id41629158919808" role="listitem"><emph>Other:</emph> MATCH and SEARCH.</paragraph>
    </listitem>
  </list>
  <h2 id="hd_id701629159564269">Examples of Wildcards in Formulas</h2>
  <paragraph role="paragraph" id="par_id271629159111490"><input>=COUNTIF(A1:A10;"Chi*")</input> counts the number of cells in the range <emph>A1:A10</emph> containing strings that starts with "Chi" followed by zero or more characters.</paragraph>
  <paragraph role="paragraph" id="par_id741629159343415"><input>=SUMIF(A1:A5;"A??";B1:B5)</input> sums the values in <emph>B1:B5</emph> whose corresponding values in <emph>A1:A5</emph> start with "A" followed by exactly two other characters.</paragraph>
  <note id="par_id141629159465592">Wildcard comparisons are <emph>not</emph> case sensitive, hence "A?" will match both "A1" and "a1".</note>

